212
00:18:43,160 --> 00:18:50,120
If someone wants to know
how we do it,
they have to pay us for our method.

213
00:18:50,120 --> 00:18:52,680
Is that a privileged technique?

214
00:18:52,680 --> 00:18:56,200
<span tts:color="lime">Absolutely, so...
We can see this, though.

215
00:18:56,200 --> 00:19:03,240
You don't give things like that
away. <font color="yellow">But we can show this.</font> Yeah,
but don't show things like that.

216
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:07,800
So, please... Please?

217
00:19:07,800 --> 00:19:10,560
Especially as Paul's not here.

218
00:19:10,560 --> 00:19:15,400
If he says it's all right, it's OK,
but otherwise, no.

219
00:19:17,800 --> 00:19:20,480
Is that one of Paul's designs?

220
00:19:20,480 --> 00:19:24,800
Yeah. He made it,
I think, or his brother.

221
00:19:25,840 --> 00:19:31,360
<span tts:color="lime">I'm going to check some other
things. I'll see you later. </span> OK.

222
00:19:33,760 --> 00:19:40,720
I hope it works for her.
They've spent a lot of money.
It's a very brave move.

223
00:19:40,720 --> 00:19:45,760
Anyone who goes into producing now
is normally very foolish,

224
00:19:45,760 --> 00:19:49,840
but at the least very, very brave.
<font color="yellow">Why?</font>

225
00:19:49,840 --> 00:19:56,080
Why? Because 95% of shows that open
lose money.

226
00:19:56,080 --> 00:20:01,720
And what do you think of the...swan?
The mechanical sawn.

227
00:20:01,720 --> 00:20:07,080
Er...personally, I wouldn't use it.
That's my opinion.

228
00:20:07,080 --> 00:20:09,600
I thought it was looking all right.

229
00:20:09,600 --> 00:20:15,360
D'you wanna say that again? <span tts:color="yellow">It
looked all right. </span> Without the smile.

230
00:20:15,360 --> 00:20:20,240
<span tts:color="yellow">It was!
</span> I think it's great, the swan(!)

231
00:20:22,360 --> 00:20:30,160
The big day - Ballet Imaginaire's
first night, and the crew are in
early getting everything in place.

232
00:20:34,400 --> 00:20:36,920
There were still some problems,

233
00:20:36,920 --> 00:20:43,960
and with Paul and I getting
on better, I saw a chance
to be involved in the production.

234
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:47,520
Would it be OK
if I pulled the swan tonight?

235
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:51,200
<font color="cyan">It would not. Ask me why.</font> Why?

236
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:56,400
You have a devious and distorted
sense of humour.

237
00:20:56,400 --> 00:21:04,240
You know if you entrusted that
to me I'd be a model of efficiency
and decorum. <font color="cyan">I don't know that.</font>

238
00:21:04,240 --> 00:21:10,280
I would expect it, but, then, you
might want to create the unexpected.

239
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:13,160
You're not in charge. Debbie is.

240
00:21:13,160 --> 00:21:16,800
This is wonderfully true.
It's great.

241
00:21:16,800 --> 00:21:22,480
I suggested to Paul that maybe
I could work the swan this evening.

242
00:21:22,480 --> 00:21:28,360
<font color="lime">That's entirely up to him.</font> You were
on the fence about it, weren't you?

243
00:21:28,360 --> 00:21:33,400
What? <font color="yellow">Me working the swan.</font> <span tts:color="lime">Not on
opening night. </span> Not on any night.

244
00:21:33,400 --> 00:21:37,240
<span tts:color="yellow">Maybe later in the run.
Not on ANY night.

245
00:21:37,240 --> 00:21:44,320
I've been getting these beautiful
flowers. <span tts:color="yellow">Oh, aren't those nice?
</span> All these good-luck cards.

246
00:21:44,320 --> 00:21:47,160
Would you like a tea or a coffee?

247
00:21:47,160 --> 00:21:51,840
'With all the first-night
preparations seemingly in hand,

248
00:21:51,840 --> 00:21:55,480
'Debbie wrote good-luck cards
to the dancers.'

249
00:21:55,480 --> 00:22:01,520
<span tts:color="lime">My husband's a real chatterbox. Can
you hear him? </span> He does go on a bit.

250
00:22:01,520 --> 00:22:04,200
Well, I mean it's nice.

251
00:22:04,200 --> 00:22:06,760
Nice to talk.

252
00:22:06,760 --> 00:22:11,400
<span tts:color="yellow">What are you doing up there?
Waiting for MY cup of tea.

253
00:22:11,400 --> 00:22:17,920
Debbie, d'you know...?
Can I say this, Paul,
what Debbie reminded you of?

254
00:22:17,920 --> 00:22:20,480
She knows already. <font color="yellow">Does she?</font> Yeah.

255
00:22:20,480 --> 00:22:26,600
The little mannequin
that separated the paragraphs
in Penthouse or Playboy.

256
00:22:26,600 --> 00:22:32,120
<font color="yellow">What did you think?</font> I'd never seen
it, so I couldn't form an opinion.

257
00:22:32,120 --> 00:22:39,000
Very attractive.
And the oddity, and it is an oddity
in this day and age of "who cares?",

258
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:43,800
is that Debbie's still
the same shape. She's fabulous.

259
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:49,440
You do have a great figure. <span tts:color="lime">Thanks.
</span> Is that part of not having children?

260
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:52,840
<font color="cyan">No.</font> No, I think... People say that,

261
00:22:52,840 --> 00:22:59,280
but look at Jane Seymour
and how many children she's had
and she's got an amazing figure.

262
00:22:59,280 --> 00:23:04,360
<span tts:color="yellow">Was there a...? Did you ever want
to have kids, Debbie? </span> No, never.

263
00:23:04,360 --> 00:23:07,200
<font color="yellow">D'you know why?</font> No, I don't.

264
00:23:07,200 --> 00:23:12,360
I didn't play with dolls
when I was little. I read books.

265
00:23:12,360 --> 00:23:17,960
There hasn't been a moment where
I've thought, "I should have one."

266
00:23:17,960 --> 00:23:25,520
<font color="lime">I've never questioned it...</font> I just
worked out that this thing I keep
sticking up my nose is a mike cover.

267
00:23:25,520 --> 00:23:28,320
<font color="yellow">Milk, Paul?</font> Milk and sugar, please.

268
00:23:28,320 --> 00:23:34,080
Is there a fear that Debbie will
become too beloved of the public?

269
00:23:34,080 --> 00:23:38,600
I am well aware
that the world of show business

270
00:23:38,600 --> 00:23:43,760
is a very...transient thing.
<font color="yellow">Yeah.</font> It just comes and it goes.

271
00:23:43,760 --> 00:23:48,840
Debbie's going into her prime,
really. <font color="cyan">Yeah.</font> Aren't you, Debbie?

272
00:23:48,840 --> 00:23:51,920
I suppose so. It does feel that way.

273
00:23:51,920 --> 00:23:57,600
<font color="lime">Yeah, it's exciting.</font> That's quite
a lot of pressure on a relationship.

274
00:23:57,600 --> 00:24:03,600
<font color="yellow">In a way, it is.</font> <span tts:color="cyan">No, it isn't.
</span> I think it depends on the people.

275
00:24:03,600 --> 00:24:10,640
The thing is with Paul is
that he has an unbelievable talent
which I know that I haven't got.

276
00:24:10,640 --> 00:24:14,840
I haven't got that extra something
he's got,

277
00:24:14,840 --> 00:24:21,000
and people who become stars like
Bruce Forsyth, Jimmy Tarbuck, Paul,

278
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:26,400
have something extra
which other performers don't have.

279
00:24:26,400 --> 00:24:32,480
Paul and Debbie throw a party
for theatre managers,
friends and family,

280
00:24:32,480 --> 00:24:36,840
including Debbie's mum, Babs,
dad, Pat, and sister, Donna.

281
00:24:36,840 --> 00:24:39,160
'This is your five-minute call.'

282
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:41,640
<font color="cyan">Enjoy it, girls.</font> Thank you.

283
00:24:43,720 --> 00:24:46,240
And then it was showtime.

284
00:24:46,240 --> 00:24:51,280
I'd never seen any ballet before,
so I didn't know what to expect.

285
00:24:51,280 --> 00:24:56,120
The show's in three parts - two
of them classical and one brand new.

286
00:24:56,120 --> 00:25:00,640
The classical sections were extracts
from Swan Lake and Coppelia.

287
00:25:00,640 --> 00:25:05,680
I couldn't follow all the action,
but the dancers seemed excellent.

288
00:25:05,680 --> 00:25:12,520
The third part was called
The Artist's Dream, with a story
by Paul and choreography by Debbie.

289
00:25:12,520 --> 00:25:17,600
It was the most interesting part,
with a West End musical feel to it,

290
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:24,760
about an artist who falls asleep
and is visited by a dream maker
who brings the painting to life.

291
00:25:24,760 --> 00:25:31,440
It also used the magical happening
designed by Paul,
built by his brother, Trevor.

292
00:25:33,560 --> 00:25:38,600
It had been a really good show
and the audience loved it.

293
00:25:52,760 --> 00:25:55,360
Well done, everybody.

294
00:25:55,360 --> 00:26:02,600
Whoa! There's people out there
from New York saying, "Never seen
anything like it." They loved you.

295
00:26:02,600 --> 00:26:08,280
Whoa-ho! That was so good. Whoa!
I might take this dancing up.

296
00:26:10,840 --> 00:26:13,480
<font color="cyan">Will you marry me again?</font> Yes.

297
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:15,920
CHEERING

298
00:26:17,160 --> 00:26:20,000
<font color="lime">Thank you, darling.</font> Wow.

299
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:25,320
Debbie, a small token of
congratulations and felicitations.

300
00:26:25,320 --> 00:26:27,960
Louis! Have we got a straw(?)

301
00:26:29,720 --> 00:26:34,840
<span tts:color="lime">Thank you. You've been so wonderful.
Thank you. Thank you.

302
00:26:34,840 --> 00:26:40,560
He's just trying to get into your
bedroom. He's been trying for weeks!

303
00:26:40,560 --> 00:26:45,680
<span tts:color="lime">But you're always there, darling.
Little old party pooper me!

304
00:26:47,880 --> 00:26:53,160
<span tts:color="cyan">You hold the matches
and you go one, two, three. </span> Oh, God.

305
00:26:53,160 --> 00:26:58,200
<span tts:color="yellow">Was Paul joking about my trying
to get in the bedroom? </span> He was.

306
00:26:58,200 --> 00:27:04,720
You haven't got to grips
with his sense of humour.
<font color="yellow">There's no such thing as a joke.</font>

307
00:27:04,720 --> 00:27:11,240
<span tts:color="yellow">He doesn't want us in there.
</span> Is he worried that you fancy me
and I fancy you?

308
00:27:11,240 --> 00:27:15,760
<span tts:color="yellow">The chemistry can't be denied.
Do we think this is true?

309
00:27:20,520 --> 00:27:24,920
Here's to Paul and Debbie
and Ballet Imaginaire.

310
00:27:26,840 --> 00:27:30,880
'Ballet Imaginaire's first night
had been a success.

311
00:27:30,880 --> 00:27:36,040
'I thought that might warrant
a drink in Paul and Debbie's room.'

312
00:27:36,040 --> 00:27:41,600
No. Remember the rules. You never
see the bedroom. Good night, Louis.

313
00:27:45,080 --> 00:27:47,600
That was a joke, right?

314
00:27:47,600 --> 00:27:49,200
Nope.

315
00:27:55,920 --> 00:28:02,880
The following morning,
and the dancers and Paul and Debbie
left to begin touring the country.

316
00:28:02,880 --> 00:28:07,400
My plan was to catch up with them
later in the tour.

317
00:28:09,160 --> 00:28:14,200
When I next checked in, the tour
had reached Stirling in Scotland.

318
00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:20,720
Things weren't going to plan.
Ticket sales were down, with Paul
blaming the petrol crisis.

319
00:28:20,720 --> 00:28:23,240
The company was losing money.

320
00:28:23,240 --> 00:28:29,120
<font color="yellow">Are you worried at all?</font> No, I have
written off the loss, mentally.

321
00:28:29,120 --> 00:28:36,240
<font color="yellow">How much?</font> Oh...shall we say...
well in excess of &#163;100,000,
you know? <font color="yellow">Yeah.</font>

322
00:28:36,240 --> 00:28:41,640
<font color="cyan">And, er...</font> Cos before you were
saying you'd not quite break even.

323
00:28:41,640 --> 00:28:47,920
I thought maybe &#163;20,000
would go down the tube.
<font color="yellow">Now it's &#163;100,000.</font> Plus.

324
00:28:47,920 --> 00:28:53,360
And you're gonna go back on the road
touring the Paul Daniels Magic Show.

325
00:28:53,360 --> 00:29:00,520
This, in terms of economics,
will be very useful
to help to fund the ballet.

326
00:29:00,520 --> 00:29:05,240
My life is now wrapped up
in the ballet and Debbie,

327
00:29:05,240 --> 00:29:10,680
so it's not just me paying my bills,
it's me keeping this product there.

328
00:29:10,680 --> 00:29:17,840
<span tts:color="yellow">How does Debbie feel about it?
</span> <span tts:color="cyan">When this hit in, Debbie, whose
initial reaction was, "Blimey...!"</span>

329
00:29:17,840 --> 00:29:23,720
<font color="yellow">When what hit in?</font> The loss.
<font color="yellow">The loss.</font> The amount of the loss.

330
00:29:23,720 --> 00:29:28,680
And the fact that the theatres
weren't going to be sold out.

331
00:29:28,680 --> 00:29:33,160
Well, we were prepared for a loss,
but not this volume.

332
00:29:33,160 --> 00:29:39,720
'With fewer than half the tickets
sold for tonight's performance,
we drummed up an audience.'

333
00:29:39,720 --> 00:29:47,320
Wanna come? <span tts:color="white">When we're finished.
</span> Just say, "Paul Daniels said
we could come and watch the ballet."

334
00:29:47,320 --> 00:29:51,440
<span tts:color="cyan">D'you wanna come and watch it?
</span> We might do, actually.

335
00:29:51,440 --> 00:29:55,800
<span tts:color="cyan">It starts in five minutes.
Paul, these guys are coming.

336
00:29:57,680 --> 00:30:03,520
<font color="yellow">They're not paying?</font> What? <span tts:color="yellow">They're
not paying? </span> I don't want them to.

337
00:30:03,520 --> 00:30:09,080
I just want 'em to get interested.
Next time we come, they'll pay.

338
00:30:09,080 --> 00:30:13,080
Please...your friends went this way.

339
00:30:14,560 --> 00:30:21,080
The next day,
Paul had been booked to appear
on Celebrity Ready Steady Cook,

340
00:30:21,080 --> 00:30:23,600
so we broke away from the tour.

341
00:30:23,600 --> 00:30:28,680
